The law itself was increasingly treated as a weapon rather than a limit. The Department of Justice indicted former FBI Director James Comey for allegedly lying to Congress, in a case that even a former Trump White House lawyer called flawed and politically motivated. The New York City Bar Association issued an unusual public statement warning against prosecutions driven by \'93impermissible motives,\'94 underscoring professional unease. In immigration, the administration fired Michele Beckwith, the acting U.S. attorney in Sacramento, hours after she reminded Border Patrol agents that they were bound by a federal court order against indiscriminate detentions. Her insistence on constitutional compliance cost her job, while the agents proceeded with a raid. In Chicago, new bodycam footage showed that the arrest of Newark\'92s mayor at an ICE facility had been ordered directly by the deputy attorney general, who also told agents to turn off their cameras. These episodes sent a clear message inside the system. Those who enforced the law against the administration\'92s wishes were vulnerable; those who bent it in service of its priorities were protected.\
\
Immigration enforcement became the sharpest edge of this approach. Over the term, the administration had already fired more than 100 immigration judges, including a third of the bench in San Francisco, and in Week 37 it emerged that 600 military lawyers had been recruited to replace them, bypassing the usual requirement of a decade\'92s experience in immigration law. Retired judges warned that these new appointees were more likely to \'93follow orders\'94 than to exercise independent judgment. At the same time, ICE stepped up deportations of long-settled southeast Asian refugees with old convictions, and the administration deported dozens of Iranians under a new deal with Tehran, despite fears of persecution on return. A Supreme Court ruling written by Justice Brett Kavanaugh held that racial profiling by ICE was permissible so long as citizens were released once they proved their status, effectively licensing race-based stops. And in Chicago, \'93Operation Midway Blitz\'94 brought militarized raids, with residents pulled from their homes, children left outside in distress, and protesters at an ICE processing center met with tear gas and pepper balls.\
