Federal power was also used to reward and punish regions at scale. During the shutdown, Office of Management and Budget Director Russ Vought announced the cancellation of nearly $8 billion in climate-related funding, concentrated in sixteen states that had not voted for Trump. He froze $18 billion in infrastructure projects in New York City, including the Hudson Tunnel and the Second Avenue Subway, on the grounds that funding should not be tied to diversity, equity, and inclusion principles. He halted $2.1 billion in federal support for Chicago transit projects, again citing concerns about race-based contracting. At the same time, the administration moved ahead with a $20 billion bailout for Argentina\'92s economy, a step seen as helpful to that country\'92s right-wing president and certain investors, even as domestic programs were starved. The pattern was stark. Blue cities and states saw climate and infrastructure funds canceled or frozen; foreign allies and favored constituencies received bailouts and targeted relief.\
