There were still pockets of ordinary governance. The Environmental Protection Agency finalized new dissolved oxygen standards for parts of the Delaware River to protect aquatic life, and approved state air quality plans in Alabama, Georgia, North Carolina, West Virginia, and the Navajo Nation. The Food and Drug Administration issued guidance on adaptive clinical trial designs, determined patent review periods for rare-disease drugs and devices, and revoked emergency authorizations for three COVID-19 vaccines now that approved alternatives were available. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention invited public comment on data collections for HIV surveillance, overdose reporting, emerging infections, and traveler risk assessment, and solicited nominations for a lead exposure advisory committee. The Federal Trade Commission unanimously authorized and filed an antitrust suit against Zillow and Redfin over alleged collusion in the rental advertising market. These actions did not reverse the week\'92s broader trends, but they showed that parts of the administrative state continued to operate on rule-bound, technocratic lines. Some habits of stewardship endured.\
